default1.1.
default 
defaultThe government would be wise to recognise and respond to the different challenges posed by generating and distributing renewable heat compared to renewable electricity. In addition, heat needs to be treated as a waste product as well as somethi
defaultng to be generated. As for electricity, there is huge potential in small and community scale generation, however ther
defaulte is also the need to introduce legislation to ensure waste heat is captured and recycled to local communities. This requires the Governmen
defaultt to expand its approach to enable investment in the installation of new infrastructure to connect heat sources to households and local businesses, and could significantly reduce energy demand for heating. 
default&#xa0;
default&#xa0;
default2.1.
default 
defaultThere is little evidence to suggest that the UK's heat demand is being significantly reduced by government policy beyond existing regulatory measures, principally the Building Regulations. 
defaultDECC's own analyses rightly point to the r
defaultole of the recession as a principle factor in the decline observed since 2008, whilst final energy consumption has rarely dipped below 140,000 thousand tonnes of oil equivalent since 1970, and 
defaultthere is good agreement when these figures are adjusted for the
default impact of temperature on energy demand.  
default 
default  
default&#xa0;
default&#xa0;
default3.1.
default 
defaultT
defaulthis is a high
defaultly contested issue that
default, in our view,
default has not yet been adequately resolved. 
defaultThe Initiative for Carbon (
defaultICARB
default)
default, in which GCU is a partner,
default has previously issued an official statement here: 
defaulthttp://icarb.org/2012/11/28/is-biomass-really-dirtier-than-coal/
